TY  - JOUR
T1  - Clients as “Partial” Employees of Service Organizations: Role Development in Client Participation
AU  - Mills, Peter K.
AU  - Morris, James H.
Y1  - 1986/10/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4283916
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4283916
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 726
EP  - 735
VL  - 11
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Clients of service organizations have important roles to perform in creating services. Yet, comparatively little attention has been directed at the participation of clients in complex and demanding client performance domains. In this paper, clients are viewed as ?partial? employees and (1) a model of client involvement stages is proposed, (2) role definition and control for clients in complex service creation are discussed, and (3) attention to issues that emerge from this discussion is encouraged.
AB  - Clients of service organizations have important roles to perform in creating services. Yet, comparatively little attention has been directed at the participation of clients in complex and demanding client performance domains. In this paper, clients are viewed as ?partial? employees and (1) a model of client involvement stages is proposed, (2) role definition and control for clients in complex service creation are discussed, and (3) attention to issues that emerge from this discussion is encouraged.
